page.text: The purpose of this study is to determine if signal is warranted at the intersection of Howell Mill
Road / White Street. A Kroger shopping center is located to the east of the study intersection in
Atlanta, Georgia. A map showing the location of the study intersection is included in Figure 1.
The study intersection is one of the access points to the existing Kroger shopping center. In order
to determine if signal is warranted at the intersection of Howell Mill Road / White Street, the
eight signal warrants described in Section 4C of the 2003 edition of the Federal Highway
Administration’s Manual on Uniform Traffic Control Devices (MUTCD) were tested using the
projected volumes. In addition to the signal Warrant analysis, existing and future capacity
analyses have also been evaluated at the study intersection.

a.m. and between 4:00 p.m. and 6:00 p.m. The four consecutive 15-minute interval volumes that

text.b: R A F F I C

page.text: In order to estimate the 24-hour and peak hour future traffic volumes that will exist at the study
intersection, it was assumed that 60% of the southbound left turn volumes that are turning on to
Bellemeade Avenue from Kroger Driveway and 30% of the northbound left turn volumes that
are turning on to Wal-Mart Driveway from Kroger Driveway will be westbound left turn
volumes on to Howell Mill Road from White Street. These traffic volumes were then added to
the existing traffic volumes in order to estimate the total future volumes at the intersection of
Howell Mill Road / White Street. The future traffic volumes at the intersection of Howell Mill
Road / White Street for the study intersection are shown in Table 3.
Future Traffic Volumes At Howell Mill Road / White Street

text.b: F u t u r e P e a k H o u r T r a f f i c

page.text: The future peak hour traffic volumes that are shown in Figure 5 were used to evaluate the future
traffic conditions at the study intersection. The results of the future traffic operation analysis
both with and without the recommended signals are shown in Tables 4 and 5.
As shown in Table 4, the eastbound and westbound approaches to the intersection of Howell
Road / White Street will experience excessive delays during both the AM and PM peak hours
without the installation of a traffic signal. Following the installation of a traffic signal, the
intersection will operate at LOS A during the AM peak hour and LOS B during the PM peak
hour. Signal warrants have been evaluated and the results are shown on pages 9 through 12. The
recommended improvements are discussed in detail in the Conclusions and Recommendations

text.b: A R R A N T
N A L Y S I S

page.text: A signal warrant analysis for the intersection of Howell Road / White Street was performed
using a main street approach speed of 35 mph with the intersection geometry of a one lane main
street and a single lane side street. To be conservative, eastbound and westbound right turn
reduction of 100% was applied for the side street to account for any right turners that may arrive
at the intersection and turn right without waiting for a gap in the southbound and northbound
through traffic on Howell Mill Road.
From the signal warrant evaluation, it was found that warrants 1, 2 and 3 are satisfied for the
proposed traffic conditions at the intersection of Howell Mill Road / White Street. A more
complete description of each warrant evaluated is as follows:
This warrant is applied where there is a large volume of intersecting traffic or where the
traffic on the main street is so heavy that traffic on a minor intersecting street suffers
excessive delay or conflict entering or crossing the major street. The required traffic
volumes must be present for at least 8 hours of an average weekday. The minimum
volumes vary according to the number of lanes on the intersecting streets, the speed of
traffic on the main street, and the community size. Two standards are evaluated that
compares specific percentages of the proposed volumes. Each standard has two
conditions: A and B. The required traffic volumes for both conditions A and B are
shown in Table 4C-1 in the MUTCD. Warrant 1 is satisfied if either Standard 1 or 2 is

This warrant is similar to warrant 1, except that the required traffic volumes must be
present for at least four hours of an average weekday. The traffic volumes required are
based on curves (Figure 4C-1 and 4C-2) shown in the MUTCD.
Number of hours required traffic present:
The Peak Hour signal warrant is applied where traffic conditions are heavy during a
minimum of one hour for an average day, causing undue delay during this time period to
side street volumes entering or crossing the major street. The MUTCD states that this
warrant is intended for application where a land use attracts or discharges a large number
of vehicles over a short time.
Number of hours required traffic present:
The pedestrian volume signal warrant is intended for application where pedestrians
experience excessive delay or an unsafe situation in crossing the major street due to the
heavy volume of traffic. This warrant evaluates the number of pedestrians during the
peak periods of an average day and the available gaps in main street traffic flow. The
pedestrian volume signal warrant shall not be applied where the distance to the nearest
traffic signal along the major street is less than 300 feet, unless the traffic signal will not
restrict the progressive movement of traffic.
An established school crossing may require signal protection if an engineering study
reveals that there is less than one gap per minute during the period of crossing usage and
there are a minimum of 20 students crossing during the highest crossing hour. The
school crossing signal warrant shall not be applied where the distance to the nearest
traffic signal along the major street is less than 300 feet, unless the traffic signal will not
restrict the progressive movement of traffic.
Warrant 6 is intended for application where a traffic signal is needed to maintain
platooning of vehicles within a coordinated signal system. This warrant should not be
applied where the resultant spacing of the signals would be less than 1,000 feet.

page.text: Signal warrants were evaluated at the intersection of Howell Mill Road / White Street that is
located in Atlanta, Georgia. The results of the signal warrant analysis indicate that the traffic
volumes at the intersection of Howell Mill Road / White Street will satisfy all three vehicular
volume signal warrants (warrants 1, 2 and 3). Therefore, it is recommended that a signal be
A left turn phase analysis was also conducted at this intersection to analyze if a protected-
permissive signal phase is required for left turn movements. The analysis results shows that the
intersections did not meet the criteria required for a protected-permissive left turn phasing for the
northbound and southbound left turn movements. Therefore, a protected-permissive signal phase
should not be installed for the northbound and southbound left turn movements. The left turn
phase criteria graphics for this intersection is included in the Appendix.
